{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"eb9280a7-2bac-4728-8034-eb8b5f46de1f","content":"## What happened\n\nApple's platform crypto libraries (`Security.framework`) have **never supported DSA**. In earlier .NET versions, `DSA.Create()` on macOS worked via an **OpenSSL interop shim**. In .NET 11, Microsoft completed the removal of that OpenSSL-based fallback on macOS, so `DSA.Create()` now throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`**.\n\nThis is part of a long-running effort to eliminate the OpenSSL dependency on macOS in favor of Apple-native APIs — but since Apple never implemented DSA, there's no native replacement.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nSince you only need to **verify** legacy signatures (not generate new ones), the cleanest fix is to use a **managed crypto library** that doesn't depend on platform primitives:\n\n**Option 1 — BouncyCastle (recommended)**\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\npublic bool VerifyDsaSignature(byte[] message, byte[] signature, DsaPublicKeyParameters publicKey)\n{\n    var signer = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA1withDSA\");\n    signer.Init(forSigning: false, publicKey);\n    signer.BlockUpdate(message, 0, message.Length);\n    return signer.VerifySignature(signature);\n}\n```\n\n**Option 2 — Platform guard with conditional OpenSSL**\n\nIf you want to keep `System.Security.Cryptography` on Windows/Linux and only fall back on macOS:\n\n```csharp\nif (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())\n    return VerifyWithBouncyCastle(message, signature, pubKey);\nelse\n    return VerifyWithSystemCrypto(message, signature, pubKey);\n```\n\n**Option 3 — Migrate off DSA entirely**\n\nDSA is deprecated (FIPS 186-5 removed it). If you control the signing side, re-sign with **ECDSA** or **Ed25519** — both are supported natively on all three platforms.\n\n### TL;DR\n\nApple never supported DSA; .NET 11 dropped the OpenSSL shim that papered over that gap. Use **BouncyCastle** for managed DSA verification, or migrate to a modern algorithm.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2b7940f0-66a6-46b8-9234-e4dee2b3f150","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me think about what I know about this topic.\n\nThis is a known breaking change in .NET. Starting with .NET 7+, Microsoft has been progressively removing support for older/weaker cryptographic algorithms on certain platforms. Specifically:\n\nIn .NET 7, several older cryptographic algorithms were deprecated or had their support reduced. But more relevantly, there's been a progression of changes around DSA support.\n\nThe key issue here is that **Apple's Security framework (CommonCrypto/Security.framework) does not support DSA**. \n\nOn macOS, .NET's crypto layer relies on Apple's native libraries, and Apple removed DSA support years ago. Earlier versions of .NET worked around this by using OpenSSL as a fallback, but starting in .NET 7, Microsoft removed that OpenSSL dependency on macOS in favor of Apple's native APIs. This means `DSA.Create()` now throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS since there's no underlying implementation available.\n\nThe user is reporting that .NET 10 worked but .NET 11 broke it, which suggests there may have been a specific breaking change introduced in .NET 11 that I don't have detailed knowledge of yet. Given the timeline and the pattern of deprecating DSA support, this could be a further tightening of the restrictions or removal of any remaining workarounds. PlatformNotSupportedException`. The workaround options are to use a third-party library like BouncyCastle for managed crypto implementations, switch to a modern algorithm like ECDSA or RSA if possible, or find an OpenSSL-based NuGet package. Looking at the .NET version history, DSA support via OpenSSL interop was available through .NET 6 but started being phased out in .NET 7 with PlatformNotSupportedException errors on macOS.\n\nGiven the user's situation where it worked on .NET 10 but broke on .NET 11, this points to Microsoft removing the last remaining DSA support path on macOS in that version. I know Apple's native crypto libraries don't support DSA, and .NET has been systematically reducing OpenSSL dependencies on macOS, so DSA being deprecated aligns with that trajectory.\n\nRather than speculate about exact version numbers, I should take the user's report at face value and focus on explaining why this happened and what they can do about it.","outputTokens":1863,"requestId":"885C:1C6615:1EE9832:2256B8B:69FA9CD0"},"id":"5ac18378-7a88-4365-a454-bb13791eb281","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:44:23.418Z","parentId":"bd6e33d5-1015-4865-a54e-ac88671b5b08"}
